['I love my iPhone 13 mini!!!', "I hate flagship phones but I bought an S23 last year because there just wasn't any small phones on the market and Zenfone and Pixel was not available in my region. Crazy how every smartphone is a giant rn, even the budget ones. Miss my Galaxy A8 (2018)", 'i live with a severe muscle disease and these big phones are just too difficult to use, it sucks having essentially ZERO options', 'Im 48 and my fingers are getting fatter, my eyesight getting worse so have the need for a larger screen although id rather have a smaller phone for the pocket space.', "The problem with iPhone mini is that mini crowd doesn't eat the same recipe for the phone. Many of my friends said they would like to buy mini but the battery life is so bad they have to stick with regular size. At the same time, not a single one cares about the thickness. Some other ones bought Pro instead because of better screen and materials. \nApple made and positioned an iPhone mini as a cheaper version of the same lineup. Which is not what mini crowd cares about. Give us thick iPhone mini with a good battery life, top notch screen and pro frame, put a price tag of Pro and 2-3 years of lifecycle. Call it iPhone Classic or something to not confuse anyone and this would be a hit IMHO", 'The 12 Mini was my favourite phone ever size wise. But it was just the worst phone ever, i had it replaced 3 Times because it randomly died on me. \nI wish they made a reliable one the Same size again.', 'I miss mini phones', 'I never wanted a big phone, with my really short fingers they are so unpractical to use. Asus had one big thing to fix, software updates. But no, lets keep that short support and make it huge!!!...', 'My pixel 3 is running out of storage but I love the phone. Perfect size, perfect specs.', "There never was a small flagship without compromises. It was always not only display size (and battery obviously) which were reduced. Sometimes it was a chip, sometimes it was display quality, sometimes it was something else. Regarding examples: zenfone for me was never an option (and will not likely be), but taking it aside, I would not ever buy a phone with such ugly bezels. Regarding iPhone, mini was not a flagship. It was not a Pro mini, it was just mini. Other mainstream like samsung almost always made performance worse. Releasing a small phone is a risky strategy. And the law is as such: if you make it too cheap it will fail. if you make it too expensive - people would think like it is less phone for the same money. Kinda like with small cars. There is no issue to have a car with a size of VW polo, but fully packed with nice materials, tech and power. There even is a VW Polo with some luxury on it, called Audi A1 nowdays. But even this car is way worse in terms of materials, features, and impression when compared to a bigger one like VW Golf or Mazda 3, even though A1 costs roughly similar to those. (35 - 37 kEUR for sporty A1 vs 35 for almost fully packed, except maybe sunroof or electric seats Mazda, vs 32 - 39 for Golf GTI). So, to produce a successful mini, it should be feature packed as the full size, does not have any cheaper materials or cutbacks as improper bezels, so basically the only diff from full size should be a display and smaller battery. It should cost lesser than full size, though. And that's the challenge cause unlikely smaller display is massively cheaper than a regular one. I can think of a one way to make smaller sells maybe - to make it significant in some way. For example, sapphire glass or some rare material can be a feature of a smaller phone, micro-led displays also. So, the price of full size and small size can be closer then. And people who likes some luxury to have something unusual might like to buy smaller one then. But again it will work only in case you can't apply these for the bigger phone yet."]

['Miss the s7 edge. Was the goat.', 'samsungs note 7 was a desaster', 'Haven‚Äôt had a galaxy s since my s10 plus and let me tell you every single one since the s2 was released was like a war of who had the latest and greatest galaxy at my job. I‚Äôve since switched to iPhone and probably won‚Äôt go back but having the most cutting edge smartphone every year was cool but very expensive.', 'S10 plus the goat', 'The Samsung Galaxy S23 Ultra operates exceptionally smoothly and reliably.', 'I miss the s7', 'S9 the most sexy ever, front and back curved glass, the black on black makes it look like a black diamond. Beautiful.', 'Watching on my Samsung Galaxy S24 Ultra 1TB ‚ù§', 'I have the s10e its still fast enough but looking to upgrade for the later One UI', "I had super basic phones in my late teen years - a black and white T9 Nokia phone and an Alcatel OneTouch Flint. Horrible experiences - basically phones from Dollar General. Getting a Samsung back in 2015 was such a magical experience - those Edge phones really felt so revolutionary back then.

My first Samsung was an S6 - really just a great introduction to the Samsung realm. Then I got the S8 Edge. Again, just such an exciting change back in 2017. But to me - and this phone isn't even mentioned in this video - the Samsung S20 FE was peak Samsung. The GOAT.

In case you didn't know, Samsung made a budget S series phone called the FE (fan edition) that had the processing power and speed of a flagship S series phone but was a few hundred dollars cheaper by cutting corners in the right places, mainly with a hard matte plastic backing and hard plastic screen. It still ran super well and was both affordable and more favourable than an A series phone (which runs and feels like a budget phone).

Nowadays, I've been sporting my S22 in that lovely jade green. What a gem. I could definitely see myself getting something different in a year or two, but it's super durable, runs like a charm, and just feels simply comfortable. The S22 may be kind of boring, but it's boring because it WORKS. Samsung may be experimenting with the software and capabilities with their newest S24 phones and the use of AI technology, but their physical form is kind of down to a science and it shows. 

iPhones have also improved spectacularly in the past few years - and I have my curious eye on the iPhone 15 - but I would recommend Samsung to anyone looking for a proper PHONE if your only main concern is a good phone and decent pair of headphones. Without any previous experience at all, most people can learn to love the newest Samsung phones if you're even lightly ambitious enough."]

['This was amazing man, the way you talk is so charismic.', "To be honest, in the first 2 minutes I started to get bored cause I thought the stuff marques says are generic and contributes nothing to the video (usually I don't get bored in marques' videos) then he said it was written by AI. Not suprised actually", '"Artists don't consent for their art to be used" 
Yeah, no. We don't have rules about learning from other people's art. You can't sell another person's drawings as yours, but you can learn to imitate their style and color palette and shapes. You are allowed to draw a picture of a Batman and the only way you can do this is by learning from existing Batman drawings. 
This is what AI does. It doesn't copy. It doesn't steal. It learns. 
And that is allowed.', 'Creativity is one of the last things AI will conquer. 
It will sooner replace technical skills like programming or drawing accurate shapes or making automated translation that sounds human. 
But creativity stems from human experience. And that would be the last thing to go. 
I dabble in AI art. People who say it isn't art are stupid. The amount of artistic choices, tweaks and references I need to make to get a good picture is significant. The difference between slop that you can generate in 5 minutes just from a prompt and a refined image is night and day.
AI is at the moment just a tool like Photoshop. People used to hate digital art and call it "not a real art" in 1990s and early 2000s. It changed. The attitude to AI art will change as well. 
The reason people hate it is because generating slop became easy. 3 years ago artists charged $50 for a generic character drawing on an empty background with simple shading. Now they can't, and that makes them upset. But what you need to recognize is that is a very low-quality work that was overpriced AF.
At the same time take best digital artists - and AI is not Even close. I am not sure if you can create a piece of artwork that is comparable with a commercial artist from a big studio. It is 80/20 rule. We got 80% of the way now and a lot of people who just want a drawing of their character are very happy with it. But if you want a production quality concept art - You will have to hire an artist. And that will be true for the next decade or two at least, at which point robots and AI will replace 60% of our jobs anyway and there will be ways to survive without a job.', 'he is being watched by the mac', 'How on earth is AI generation violating copyright? The whole point of art and creative work is to express yourself freely as you want no matter what style the type of art has. 

Just because your art has a very similar or basically even identical inspired style to someone else's art it is not at all wrong. 

Even with music it's the same: Imagine you just naturally have almost the same voice as Drake or you're an impersonator and create music where your voice sounds exactly like Drake this should never be copyrighted because it's created by you from scratch and is unique, it's not as if you leak confidential audio recordings of the real Drake and publish them without his consent because in the other case it's your own unique content and you don't even have to use the same name of a popular person or existing trade marked company name and can just call the artist name Dake instead of Drake for example.

Just because an AI isn't human it doesn't make it different. AI is literally based on the same nature or brains work with neural networks and is doing the exact same thing like a human: copying work from others "in their brains" and recreating it.

No one owns a voice tone or type of art style, that's the whole point of art in my opinion to freely express yourself and everything against this is oppressing that.

That are just greedy people in my opinion who don't care about that and just want to suck out money out of everything.

If you're inspired by Picasso's art style and draw exactly like him or have the exact same voice like Drake that's perfectly fine and doesn't mean you're not allowed to make music just because your voice sounds like Drake, no matter if you're a human, dog or AI.

This whole legal debacle should've long been easily eliminated because of this basic common sense in my opinion.', '"not to take my job" - but to take others. got it.......', 'The fact that I went ‚ÄúI am getting all the information I need in the first couple minutes‚Äù and then realized ‚Äúwait, this is an MKBHD video, they aren‚Äôt this short‚Äù', 'i think there must be another app to validate what AI generated in some specific subject.', 'Has anyone else watched the terminator movies? Turn them off.']

['Down to 199 now üòä', 'Absolutely love my cute Pixel 6a :3 woohoo ‚ù§', "Google sent me this phone new to replace my Pixel 5a which suffered the common and predicted motherboard death (Google extended the warranty for exactly this reason).  Although I am benefitting from the extended software/security support period of the 6a, I have mixed feelings about the phone.  Unlike the 5a, the fingerprint sensor is very unreliable.  If your fingers are cold, or wet, or you are outside in bright sunlight, it is almost certain to fail.  The 5a had a headphone jack.  The 6a does not.  The 6a is VERY narrow, which means the keyboard is cramped, resulting in a LOT more typos than with the broader 5a.  Battery life on the 6a is a downgrade from the impressive 5a.  I have had no issues with the auto brightness, but in bright sunlight the screen is hard to see.  As for the camera, it's not great.  It cannot process aqua colors, and most photos are muted compared with reality.  Detail is limited. The water resistance rating for the 6a is lower than the 5a, but practically I will probably never notice the difference.  I hear what the reviewer is saying about the refresh rate and choppiness, but I have not found that to be a big deal.  I have not noticed any of the rainbow effects he referred to.  I will say that the 6a is the first phone I've had that both feels and looks FAR better in a phone case than in the raw. In a wood backed case the camera band actually looks slick and streamlined, rather than cheap and sharp edged like it does naked.  The speed of the phone is adequate, but so was the 5a. What kind of a dumb question is that? Why would you want to make a robot to do human things? Really Marques? Tesla is a business what do you think they will do with those robots? üòÇ", 'Over 2 years later and we are almost there', 'Humans aren‚Äôt actually that efficient for many things we would want to use robots for. Why make it human shaped?', 'Amazing to see how far we‚Äôve come', "Dangerous, repetitive and boring isn't most of the task comes under this. Maybe except art and tech.", 'Marques ... I feel like you answered a question you proposed in your video without realizing it. You asked why build a robot that is humanoid then you proceeded to say that the only reason our bodies are as functional as they are is because we have built the world to be functional for our bodies.  You said that if we wanted a robot that could do something that we would build a robot that does that job specifically and it would be great at that job (better than a humanoid version).  Well, here\'s the issue ... we already do that.  But why build a new robot to perform a specific task EVERY single time we have a new task when we could build a humanoid robot which can then be programmed to do that task.  If I own a robot that can make my bed ... and I want one that can cook me a 4 course meal ... I\'d need someone to design and build a new robot that does just that and then after they did that ... I\'d have to buy that robot too.  But if I make a humanoid robot, I can just program it to do each task because we already know a human can perform that task because we\'ve done it with that body for centuries (and everything we have to do it is designed for the human body).  So rather than designing and purchasing an entirely new robot every time, we just take our existing humanoid robot that is performing tasks already in our house and download the "cook me dinner" software and we are off and running.  Sure, a custom designed robot for every task is going to be more efficient ... but a humanoid robot could theoretically do EVERY task a human can already do without any new hardware ... its just software at that point.  THAT is why they want to design it as a humanoid ... so that it can utilize every tool we have created throughout time to accomplish tasks just like any human.  Why reinvent the wheel every time we want a new task done when a humanoid robot can do what we can do (theoretically speaking).']

And while the original iPad seemed to be Apple's idea of a netbook, the modern iPads have gone so far beyond that that there's little difference in capability between their laptops and tablets, except where they make it.

Apple has a lot going for it, but being the cutting-edge master of technology is definitely not part of the equation. Their latest innovation is really a vast improvement over their ARM chips for phones and tablets. A previous one was using USB-C exclusively on their laptops starting with the 12-inch MacBook. And let's all remember the removal of the headphone jack and phone chargers! I assume there's a ton of software ideas they've implemented, but none of them have been so far ahead of the competition that they can be claimed as innovations. Apple AirTags came out after Tile.

I just don't think Apple is an exciting company. I was sold on them after my recent frustrations with Chromebooks and Chrome OS. There's no way I want a Windows laptop and I don't want to be bothered getting one only to install Linux on it. I'd buy a MacBook because everything is so polished. But as far as I can tell, everything about Apple that could be called "new" isn't any more exciting than the latest indie game, mouse, TV, or law concerning our privacy rights. Apple just has a nicer package and presentation but their stuff is just a somewhat higher-quality version of stuff we've already seen.

Apple is just a highly successful business that depends heavily on keeping up appearances and being just competitive enough that those already invested in Apple remain convinced that Apple's still the best. They are not the stupendous company some of us wish they were and they will never do anything so much better than the competition that it changes everything. Even their Apple silicon is limited to their own products and most everyone else is satisfied with the ARM processors in their phones already.

I need to stop checking videos like this hoping it's something worth my attention. Apple, frankly, is just a very polished utility that refuses to outdo itself against its own financial self-interests, especially if it exposes just how utterly limited they are in their vision and willingness to be more than they already are and have been since Steve Jobs died.', 'I think the idea is simple. If iPad as a personal PC can wreck all category of markets (windows / Linux) then Apple go for making iPad a PC. They have no reason to dumb Mac otherwise. They evolve their products at the cost of another often to conquer markets across the spectrum. Like how iPhone killed iPod but iPhone also wrecked across the market giving them so much new money.', 'Ipad has the same problem as Iphone. Their OS is locked üîí and will remain locked üîí.

 The devices are deliberately handicapped to force you to "buy the whole lineup" or "full ecosystem". An Ipad will never do what a Mac can because than you dont buy the whole ecosystem...it just shrunk by a device and Apple's profits shrunk.

For some reason the limitations bother me more on the iPhone than on the Ipad since I need my phone to do more. I've been okay using an Ipad for the odd Facetime call, email and as a media consumption device... but now Im questioning that.

Currently I use a Samsung Galaxy Note 20 Ultra and every other device is Apple. However, I am considering ditching the Ipad and only using Mac. 

It seems as though Samsung tablets are now better than Ipads simply because they are free devices that you fully own and can do anything you want with. 

Older Samsungs lacked the power to really be usable but current gen are great tablets but can function as Chrome OS devices as well so you have full computer level functionality when you need it and full tablet functionality when you need it... something the Ipad can't offer.

The only drawbacks with Samsung tablets are they dont seem to be made to be used in portrait mode... primarily landscape. I'm a musician and like to use a tablet for lyrics. Also, there are a few pesky apps not available on Android yet. Lumafusion going to Android is cool...but there are others I need. The growth of ChromeOS also causes Dex Mode in Samsung devices to get better. Hopefully soon it will have evolved to the point that it is as powerful as Mac OS or Windows.

I don't know what to do...maybe time to go to Best Buy and compare the devices in store.']

I never got to use it.  only good for transfering to different devices.  redundancy is very common among useres.", 'I rlly want it but it expensive :(', "Man Samsung has been trying to remove their SD card slot for a while (along with swapable batteries, which they succeeded with the S6 onward). If you recall, the S6 had no expandable storage, but they brought it back for the S7...not sure if that was an unpopular removal back then. With the S6 they were able to sell the new build quality improvements of metal/glass (S5 and earlier were all mostly plastic builds).

Non swapable batteries and no SD card slot not only simplifies building the phone, but also is great for planned obsolescence. Need more memory? Need a new phone! Battery not what it used to be? Need new phone! (I suppose you can swap it, but it is not easy and many will opt for a new phone rather than replacing their existing battery).

The non expandable storage also gives them more control over pricing. They can offer you a higher capacity phone but you have to buy the additional capacity through them rather than through an SD card of your choice.

Is the SD card dying? I'm sure some underdogs will keep it around as a differentiating feature along with headphone jacks. I feel like Sony flagships for example still have the headphone jacks and sd card slots, but I could be wrong?", 'What about the S21 FE ? It's still buttery smooth and the way it fits in the hand is better than any phone I've ever used‚Äîand most definitely better than the current crop of flagships.

I hadn't reset my phone in over 2.5 years and it had become slow as molasses, so I briefly considered upgrading to the S22. I went to the store and tried it out, but it felt like a significant downgrade from the S10e. It's not just the fact that it's larger but the chunkier squared off sides made it much less comfortable to hold and use than my phone.

I came home and reset my phone that night and restored it from backups. I lost no data and it became as fast and smooth as new. It's been one month since then and I'm so glad I didn't pull the trigger on the S22.

I've dropped it innumerable times, in every manner and on every surface conceivable, but it's withstood everything beautifully. I've had to get the rear glass replaced a couple of times, the front glass once, and the camera glass cover once‚Äîall of which cost me peanuts compared to what it does on the newer devices.

I've never put a case on it, before or after the shatters, and it wears the dings and scratches with pride. It's a solid, well built and well used phone.

I sometimes wonder whether the people at Samsung who designed these phones realise what an absolute gem this phone is. Don't they use it alongside the newer devices and realise that we're going back in terms of quality?

I know to many of you the 90s were a time of backwards barbarism and you look at the 90s the way I looked at the 1970s or 60s, but as a teenager in the 90s I remember thinking these predictions were VERY COOL, but not unfathomable, they took existing technology and made educated guesses on where it would go. AT&T was also working with several tech companies, so they knew where this was all headed. They made realistic, grounded guesses, not sci-fi movie stupid guesses like flying cars or hoverboards. Touch screen tech was around way before the 1990s, it was even around in the 1960s, but not in the public domain.   The movie Die Hard in 1988 had the hero John McClane use a touch screen in the hotel that got hijacked, I used a touch screen in Disney World with my family in 1990.  Again, a lot of these technologies were in the embryonic phase in the early 90s, I remember thinking it was really cool in 1993 the idea you could do your homework with someone on the other side of the planet....by 1999 and 2000 this was a reality.', "In 2023 we don't have Google Glass anymore unfortunately but we have something similar coming next year called Apple Vision Pro that seems to be the next big thing. I have repaired two S22 Ultra's and one S23 because my kids are hard on them. I'm not a repair guy, just like doing them for myself. There is no way I would ever purchase anything apple.", 'if was becuase fake face scanner, apple could of SEPERATED what is a false face scanner, and what is simply a false scree, what if rich AF and atualy want screen that is BETTER thats still "not genuine" but still like apple?', 'wonder if repair shops then ever jailbreak phones just to change geo location to repair anywhere?', 'Another reason to never buy anything from Apple or an iPhone in general', "As someone Who was Trained in Apple repairs for Warrenty repairs (third-Party through Carriers insurance warranty) There was NO way (as of 2024 January)to Purchase Backglasses, with the backglass it was IMPOSSIBLE to get there, was no way to buy them. we could not sell them as OEM because Apple didnt sell them. so they had to be devoid of the Apple Logo. just sleek flat glass. I actually prefered the Logo-less back if I'm honest.
also there has got to be no way true tone was gonna work past an update. We had a program given to us by Apple that allowed us to update the part in their servers so the Batteries and Screens worked.(cameras and  face ID were NOT allowed in our business)", 'We're talking about Apple here -- a company that's always had total control over its hardware and OS - they do this on their computing side of the house -- and it's no surprise that they are doing it on the mobile/tablet side now.

Especially with the use of Security Devices (like face scanners and finger print detection) -- these security devices -- usually require some kind of Certificate Authority (CA) to certify  they are legit devices - but more than likely  have some kind of TPM chip embedded in the device that was registered post production of the iPhone and registered with verisign or their own CA server that links up with their iCloud servers for the said Serial#+HardwareSerial#  before it went on sale to the masses

and so the Certified Technician (@ ~3:30 in to the video)  --was really was just describing -what is known in the Cyber Security community-  as a CRL (Certificate Revocation) of the old certs tied to the old hardware (broken screen or camera) and pairing it with a new one (or Certificate Renewal) which creates a new "authorized" bond of the devices -- at least on the CA and/or the iCloud Servers.
 If a hardware mismatch occurs - it basically nulls that certificate and iCloud servers cannot determine if the hardware on the iPhone is genuine or not - because they were not the ones issuing it. 
i mean honestly - It could have been parts from a stolen/Lost iPhone sold as parts to repair shops and them using it to common repairs to regular consumers.

But with that said, this is what makes it a challenge for 3rd party repair shops to do these types of repairs on newer models- because they've been in the business of swapping out bad hardware with similar replacements and calling it good and charging the consumer for it. Newer devices - with newer features require tighter integration with OS and Hardware-- These types of integration can only be done by Apple themselves -- since they have total control over both the iOS Servers for the OS and the Hardware that they produce. any counterfeits or stolen parts -- make stealing these devices and reselling them -- pretty useless -- and perhaps that is what they were going for? <shrugs>

So essentially, these repair shops are just brokering or reaching out to apple on your behalf and requesting the genuine parts to swap out - while charging you an overhead margin fee on top of that. (which is why it cost more than just going directly to Apple)
I'll just stick to my  PixelPro  - wifey still uses iPhone - but i guess we have to use the genus bar from now  on to do repairs. Which kind of sucks for the repair shop industry.']

["A few updates after having seen the response to this video:

1.\xa0From the feedback I've gotten, Pokemon Unite is one of the less malicious Free-to-Play games in this genre.\xa0I still stand by the fact that it employs manipulative strategies to earn more from players, but in hindsight there were a few things I could have done to save me spending quite as much as I did. That said, I don't want this to take away from the key message of the video, which still stands and is still incredibly important. 

2. Most of the shots in the video and screen recordings were sourced by my editor on my editors account, and so are more to demonstrate the points being made, as opposed to being representative of my own gameplay.

3. I've been informed that it is currently possible to upgrade an item to level 30 without paying real money in Pokemon Unite - this hasn't always been the case and isn't made clear to the player - it seems to be a limited time thing - but nonetheless an oversight on my part!

4. I am completely happy to admit that I am far from the best Pokemon Unite player. If the upgrade worth it', 'I like how they removed the lense housing because, with a case, it protects them and makes the overall phone slimer with one while offering protection', 'One of the biggest problems with this YouTuber's channel is their constant focus on comparing smartphones to the latest iPhone and Samsung flagship models. It feels like they always push the message that you "have to" have the newest and most expensive phone to get a good mobile experience.
But the reality is that at least 50% of us are looking for good performance at a reasonable price. And this is where the channel really fails. They rarely mention more affordable options like Motorola or Xiaomi, which often offer significantly more for the money.

This problem can be summarized in the following points:

1. Unrealistic picture of the smartphone market: Focusing solely on the most expensive models gives a skewed picture of the smartphone market. Most people cannot afford an iPhone or Samsung Galaxy S-series, and there are many other excellent options at a lower price.

2. Ignoring affordability: The channel does not take enough into account affordability. They seem to think that the only thing that matters is performance, regardless of the price tag. But for many users, the budget is an important factor, and they want to get the most out of their money.

3. Missing out on good options: By focusing solely on iPhones and Samsung flagship models, the channel misses out on many good options from other manufacturers. Motorola and Xiaomi are just two examples of brands that offer excellent smartphones at a significantly lower price.

4. Creates a feeling of inadequacy: Constantly seeing reviews of expensive smartphones can make viewers feel inadequate if they cannot afford such a phone. This can lead to dissatisfaction with their own phone and a feeling that they are not getting the best that the market has to offer.', 'Personally, I think Samsung absolutely perfected their smartphone design language and created the most aesthetically appealing looking phone design ever made with the introduction of the Samsung Galaxy S22 Ultra.
